{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584331"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:43:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:43:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14440"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14440"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.2,0.6,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7135"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60122"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7135"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14440"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45542"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4903"},{"type":"tags","id":"4905"},{"type":"tags","id":"4909"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8423"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17039"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17139"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60122"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following ions induces calcium ion release through the ryanodine receptor-channels in cardiomyocytes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Potassium ions","Sodium ions","Calcium ions","Magnesium ions","Chloride ions"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium ions\u003C/strong\u003E, which play a key role in inducing calcium release through a process known as calcium-induced calcium release (CICR). When calcium ions enter the cell via L-type calcium channels during the action potential, they bind to ryanodine receptor (RyR) channels on the sarcoplasmic reticulum, triggering the release of additional calcium ions stored within the sarcoplasmic reticulum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium ions\u003C/strong\u003E are important for the initial depolarisation of the cardiomyocyte membrane but do not directly trigger calcium release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum. \u003Cstrong\u003EPotassium ions\u003C/strong\u003E are primarily involved in repolarisation of the cell membrane. \u003Cstrong\u003EChloride ions\u003C/strong\u003E play a minor role in maintaining the resting membrane potential but do not directly influence calcium release. \u003Cstrong\u003EMagnesium ions\u003C/strong\u003E can modulate calcium channel function but do not directly induce calcium release through ryanodine receptor-channels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe calcium-induced calcium release mechanism amplifies the initial calcium influx, leading to a significant increase in intracellular calcium concentration. This increase in calcium is necessary for the activation of contractile proteins in cardiomyocytes, resulting in heart muscle contraction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calcium ions trigger calcium release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum through ryanodine receptor-channels in cardiomyocytes, a process known as calcium-induced calcium release."],"references":["Tortora, G. J., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Cooke, J., Di Pietro, F., Diversi, T., ... \u0026 Summers, S.. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 3rd Asia-Pacific Edition. 2022. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Lanner JT, Georgiou DK, Joshi AD, Hamilton SL. Ryanodine receptors: structure, expression, molecular details, and function in calcium release. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2010 Nov;2(11):a003996. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a003996. Epub 2010 Oct 20. PMID: 20961976; PMCID: PMC2964179."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45542"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14440"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45542"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-10T09:59:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-10T10:00:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7135"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60122"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifyi